\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {28}{\ignorespaces The W spider in ZW calculus represents the N-partite W state. The W spider with $N$ legs encodes the superposition where exactly one qubit is in state $|1\rangle $ and the rest are $|0\rangle $, with all permutations equally weighted. W spider (purple): The fundamental primitive for genuine $N$-partite entanglement. Unlike Z spiders that represent computational basis states, W spiders explicitly capture multipartite correlations that survive tracing. $|W_N\rangle = \frac  {1}{\sqrt  {N}}(|10\ldots  0\rangle + |01\ldots  0\rangle + \cdots  + |00\ldots  1\rangle )$.}}{23}{figure.28}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:zw-w-spider}{{28}{23}{The W spider in ZW calculus represents the N-partite W state. The W spider with $N$ legs encodes the superposition where exactly one qubit is in state $|1\rangle $ and the rest are $|0\rangle $, with all permutations equally weighted. W spider (purple): The fundamental primitive for genuine $N$-partite entanglement. Unlike Z spiders that represent computational basis states, W spiders explicitly capture multipartite correlations that survive tracing. $|W_N\rangle = \frac {1}{\sqrt {N}}(|10\ldots 0\rangle + |01\ldots 0\rangle + \cdots + |00\ldots 1\rangle )$}{figure.28}{}}
\newlabel{fig:zw-w-spider@cref}{{[figure][28][]28}{[1][23][]23}}
